class Solution {
public:
    int removeElement(vector<int>& nums, int val) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int s = 0, e = n-1;
        int cnt = 0;
        while(s<=e){
            if(nums[s]!=val){
                s++;
                cnt++;
            }
            else{
                swap(nums[s],nums[e]);
                e--;
            }
        }
        return cnt;
    }
};

"Idea:
Use two pointers: s starting from the beginning and e from the end of the array.
The goal is to move all occurrences of val towards the end of the array.
Traverse the array while s <= e.
If nums[s] is not equal to val, it is a valid element, so increment cnt and move s forward.
If nums[s] == val, swap it with nums[e] so the unwanted element goes to the back.
Decrease e after swapping because the last position is now processed.
Finally, cnt represents the number of elements remaining after removing val.
Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
"
